<TEXT>
the young man once known to the country as 
johnjohn son of the democrats martyred president brought 
convention delegates to their feet cheering tuesday night and told 
them because of you he is with us still 
and later the five children of jesse jackson introduced their 
father the candidate to a hall so crowded they locked the doors 
hundreds of delegates reporters and convention guests were 
stopped by a police line after the fire marshal ordered that the 
omni arena could hold no more 
jackson shared his big moment before the convention with the 
woman whose refusal to give up her seat on a bus in montgomery 
ala more than a quarter century ago began the turnaround in 
american race relations 
all of you think you are seated he said as he introduced 
rosa parks but youre really standing on someones shoulders 
the convention hall was a waving sea of red jesse signs as 
the runnerup in the nominee race appeared after his children 
introduced him onebyone not a single blue sign for michael 
dukakis the democratic nomineetobe could be seen 
the delegates to the democratic national convention had been a 
rather undemonstrative lot until they welcomed john f kennedy jr 
with a twominute standing ovation 
over a quarter century ago my father stood before you to 
accept the nomination for president said the 27yearold 
kennedy and then he introduced his uncle who he said inspired his 
generation 
as if to show that the kennedy name still carries magic the 
delegates stood and cheered again for sen edward f kennedy the 
dead presidents brother and johnjohns uncle teddy 
it was a fitting prelude for the big show yet to come jacksons 
closing speech of his long campaign for the presidency 
kennedy a spellbinding speaker didnt disappoint the 
convention until he arrived many seats were still empty like 
magic they filled 
where was george he asked repeatedly 
and the delegates responded with a cascading chant where was 
george where was george 
said kennedy we all know the answer to all these questions 
george bush is the man who is never there and he wont be there 
after the clock strikes noon on jan 20 1989 
in fact sen kennedy was the second speaker of the evening to 
bring up where was george earlier in the evening rep tony 
coelho of california recited a similar litany and got a similar 
response 
the two speakers may have been telegraphing a battle cry for the 
campaign to come 
the question caused banners to bob up and down in the hall the 
red jesse signs as well as the redwhite and blue posters 
saying dukakis for president 88 
</TEXT>
