<TEXT>
communist rebels rejected new peace 
talks with president corazon aquino as a farce monday charging 
her government and the military merely wanted to trap leaders of 
the 19yearold insurgency 
selfstyled communist rebels meanwhile killed a provincial 
official monday and a guerrilla spokesman warned of more killings 
as long as the government fails he said to prosecute human rights 
violators in the military 
the general command of the communist new peoples army in a 
statement sent by courier to news agencies claimed mrs aquinos 
government lost its credibility following the collapse of peace 
talks last year 
mrs aquino has said she would agree to new peace talks if the 
rebels made the first move 
defense secretary fidel ramos said the defense department and 
the 250000member armed forces would abide by her decision ramos 
earlier turned down the possibility of reviving the talks saying 
it would only give the rebels time to regroup 
the president has spoken ramos told reporters i dont 
think there is anyone that will oppose any objective such as 
obtaining peace but it must be peace with justice and honor 
the rebel statement was in response to a call last week by the 
influential catholic bishops conference of the philippines for the 
government and the guerrillas to call for a new ceasefire and 
revive peace talks 
history repeats itself twice the first as tragedy the second 
as farce the statement said 
we cannot respond positively to a call for a new 
ceasefire that will mean the annihilation of the revolutionary 
movement and its mass base we have learned our lessons well from 
the duplicity of the aquino government and its military 
establishment 
the rebels accused the government of insincerity and charged 
that what the government and the military establishment sought to 
lay down was a trap that played on the good faith of the leaders of 
the revolutionary movement 
about five members of the communist partys central committee 
and dozens of its regional leaders were captured by the military in 
raids after the 60day ceasefire lapsed in february 1987 
on sunday the rebels southern luzon command said it was 
agreeable to peace talks in principle but claimed the government 
was setting unacceptable conditions 
in a related development police said two men who claimed to be 
communist guerrillas barged into a government office on monday in 
lucena 60 miles southeast of manila and shot dead city councilor 
donaldo alfaro 54 
alfaro belonged to a government group organized to help the 
military curb rebel infiltration of local neighborhoods 
arnel sandoval spokesman of the alex boncayao brigade 
justified the guerrillas continuing attacks on police soldiers 
and government officials by claiming the government failed to 
prosecute notorious police and military human rights violators 
the brigade is a manilabased unit of the rebel army that has 
claimed responsibility for killing more than 100 police soldiers 
and officials during the past year 
in bulacan province police monday arrested two suspected rebels 
who killed a policeman a day earlier in baliwag just north of 
manila 
a gunman monday fatally shot vice mayor daud talib on the island 
of jolo about 600 miles south of manila police said 
the area is a stronghold of moslem separatist guerrillas 
