<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency has added 
six major estuaries to a list of ecologically sensitive coastal 
areas targeted for study on ways to improve their health and clean 
them up 
placed on the list monday were galveston bay texas delaware 
bay and delaware inland bay del the new yorknew jersey harbor 
sarasota bay fla and santa monica bay calif 
estuaries where rivers meet the sea and fresh water mixes 
with salt water serve as the principal spawning grounds and 
nurseries for at least twothirds of the nations commercial 
fisheries and are home to valuable and diverse species of fish 
shellfish and wildlife the epa said 
they also are sources of irreplaceble recreation and aesthetic 
enjoyment the agency said 
estuaries are clearly in trouble threatened by toxic and 
bacterial contamination industrial and municipal sewage 
discharges agricultural runoff oxygendepleted waters and loss of 
fish and wildlife habitat said epa regional administrator robert 
e layton jr in dallas 
under the national estuary program the bay studies are designed 
to come up with recommendations for longterm strategies for 
pollution control and resource management epa officials said 
epa spokesman dave ryan said the studies which can take as long 
as five years are a joint effort of the agency and state and local 
officials with states contributing 25 percent of the costs 
the estuary program was established as part of the water quality 
act of 1987 to identify and protect significant estuaries 
a dozen estuaries are targeted for priority in the program 
including the six named monday the other six were included in the 
program last year albemarlepamlico sound nc buzzards bay 
mass long island sound ny narragansett bay ri puget 
sound wash and san francisco bay 
</TEXT>
