<TEXT>
two government reports question the 
effectiveness of us assistance to egypt and cast doubt on whether 
the aid has brought about policy changes sought by the reagan 
administration 
a general accounting office study of us aid to seven 
countries of which egypt is the most populous concluded that the 
agency for international development has had mixed success in 
encouraging foreign policy reforms 
another report from aid inspector general hebert l beckington 
criticized the use of 15 billion worth of machinery and equipment 
sent to egypt between 1975 and 1986 
egypt got 8197 million in economic support funds from the 
united states in fiscal 1987 second only to israel 
aid spokesman timothy oleary said monday that 115 million of 
the aid was transferred in cash to the government of president 
hosni mubarak most of the rest was spent on projects designed to 
raise the countrys standard of living 
the gao report said the cash transfer to egypt was based on a 
document that described broad policy changes that the us 
government expected from egypt but gave no details on how progress 
would be measured 
the report dated june 29 and made public this month added that 
while the document listed egyptian policy reforms since the 
previous transfer it did not explain their meaning or how they 
related to what the united states sought 
egypt has not moved quickly enough to adopt the economic 
reforms necessary to address the numerous and costly inefficiencies 
that pervade the egyptian economy it said 
the state department in a comment included in the gao report 
said there are countries where setting reform targets in advance 
will fuel political opposition on the grounds that foreigners are 
dominating economic policy 
in some situations a less specific economic reform program 
may be preferable to a highly specific program with unrealistic 
expectations eugene j mcallister assistant secretary of state 
for economic affairs stated in the report 
the aid report on egypts use of usfinanced machinery and 
equipment blamed the inability of the egyptian government aid and 
contractors to coordinate procurement with actual construction 
large amounts were either not being used or used at levels 
much below what was anticipated the report said of the equipment 
the report issued about the same time as the gao document also 
cited the limited capability of government of egypt entities to 
operate and maintain machinery and equipment 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

