<TEXT>
thousands of peasants rioted in a ripe watermelon 
field and hundreds of urban dwellers looted a melon stand official 
reports said in the latest replay of the melon madness that hits 
china each summer 
participants in similar melonlooting sprees last summer 
received heavy prison terms and growers and sellers this year have 
resorted to hiring police guards apparently to little avail 
chinese eat millions of watermelons during the summer nearly 
at a rate of one a day per person in cities and some literally go 
mad over them 
in one of the latest looting incidents about 2000 peasants 
swarmed onto a melon field in central chinas henan province and 
snatched 500000 pounds of the juicy fruit in raids july 8 and 9 
the legal daily fazhi ribao on monday carried a blurry picture 
of dozens of people running through the field grabbing melons in 
both arms it said police tried to restore order but were roughed 
up by the looters 
the growers 25 peasants who had jointly contracted to plant the 
land could only put their heads down and cry in the fields 
the national newspaper said 
in a separate incident in northeastern chinas jilin province 
the legal daily said hundreds of people in songjianghe town looted 
a melon stand over several days in early july grabbing 60000 
pounds of melon 
at first the melon owner had hired protectors who fended 
off thieves but three men beat up the protectors on july 6 and 
several hundred people began snatching fruit the report said 
several suspected looters were arrested but all later were 
released without charges it said without elaborating 
in last summers most spectacular melon riot nearly 100 melon 
vendors raided a beijing train depot where farmers had brought in 
melons under contract to other vendors 
the raiders beat up some of the farmers and made off with 55000 
pounds of the fruit two of the thieves were sentenced to life in 
prison and six recieved two to 12 years in jail 
also last summer more than 100 people in jilin province jumped 
on trucks carrying melons into the provincial capital jilin and 
stole 22000 pounds farmers and bystanders who tried to protect 
shipment were beaten 
beijing authorities announced measures in june to ensure an 
adequate supply of melons to the city at controlled prices partly 
in hopes of heading off violent grabs for the fruit 
they lifted the usual ban on bringing tractors and horsedrawn 
carriages into the city center so that farmers could easily get the 
melons to market and set up designated melon marketplaces 
so far no melon violence has been reported in the capital 
</TEXT>
