<TEXT>
from tripledigit inflation to a crushing 
104 billion foreign debt presidentelect carlos salinas de 
gortari faces a series of challenges that would have made some of 
his 60 predecessors wince 
horrendous unemployment a ballooning population and growing 
discontent with the political party that has run mexico since 1929 
further threaten to make salinas inaugural term something less 
than a picnic in the park 
by the time salinas leaves office in six years mexicos 
population is expected to have grown by about 10 million to 91 
million all crammed in an area three times the size of texas 
unless he can reverse the trends that growth will mean more 
people for fewer jobs 
with about half the current population under age 16 it is 
estimated that by the time salinas term ends about 1 million 
young people a year will be looking for work for the first time 
a recent study by the national manufacturers chamber showed that 
only 350000 jobs were created last year a drop from the previous 
year 
another study by salinas institutional revolutionary party 
said roughly 28 percent of mexicos labor force of 47 million 
people lack steady jobs and 14 percent are jobless a total of 42 
percent 
inflation which reached a 1592 percent annual rate last year 
has eroded the average purchasing power of wages by more than half 
salinas says one of his priorities will be to restore the value 
of earnings 
we will have to provide that and also housing education 
health care and other basic services not only to cut deficits 
but also for the 6 million new jobseekers who will emerge during 
his administration salinas said in a recent interview with the 
television network televisa 
if foreign debt payments become too burdensome they will be 
renegotiated or suspended altogether he added 
a survey by the governing party think tank the institute of 
political economic and social studies indicates that gross fixed 
investment has been dropping by an annual average of nearly 5 
percent with a drop of 12 percent in 1986 
for decades illegal emigration of millions of mexicans to the 
united states acted as an escape valve for the population problem 
but a 1987 law in the united states that fines employers who 
knowingly hire illegal aliens could shut or narrow the aperture 
as budget and planning secretary for five years in outgoing 
president miguel de la madrids administration salinas was 
associated with belttightening and other unpopular measures 
both the governing partys labor wing and its old guard strongly 
opposed his nomination so salinas is now busy trying to mend 
fences especially with fidel velazquez the 88yearold leader of 
the mexican labor federation 
the centrist institutional revolutionary party or pri has won 
every major election since it was founded in 1929 its critics 
claim it often resorts to ballot fraud 
charges of vote fraud were louder than ever this year as the 
government delayed release of results until a week after the july 6 
balloting and then said salinas won with just over 50 percent of 
the vote 20 percent less than previous pri presidential victories 
the pris patronage system still goes deep into the countrys 
grass roots but its power base has been eroding under pressure 
from growing forces on both the left and right 
many say the party has been unable or unwilling to meet 
mexicos increasingly greater demands for more orderly government 
less corruption greater economic development and more efficient 
state services 
the disillusionment cuts across social and political lines 
people are clamoring against everything from a selfmuzzled press 
to deficient law enforcement to lack of environmental protection to 
neglect for womens rights 
the conservative national action party and the leftist coalition 
national democratic front have been addressing these issues and 
picking up votes 
for the first time in decades the governing partys 
presidential candidate actually had to campaign on the basis of 
concrete solutions to specific issues from smog in mexico city to 
the drug problem to a growing crime rate 
salinas acknowledges these challenges saying reforms and 
modernization will be the priorities of his administration 
hell begin trying on dec 1 the date he officially takes 
office 
