<DOCNO> AP880719-0078 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
consumer prices jumped 19 percent in the past 
year the government announced today acknowledging the biggest 
such rise since china introduced market reforms a decade ago 
zhang zhongji a spokesman for the state statistics bureau 
blamed the economys inability to satisfy consumer demand for the 
rise but he said middlemen who hoard goods and control their 
distribution also are responsible 
zhang also told a news conference that grain production 
stagnant for the past two years is not expected to improve this 
year 
he said workers in chinas 32 major cities including beijing 
shanghai and wuhan were hardest hit by inflation and that food 
prices increased the most 
prices last month were 19 percent higher than those of june 
1987 he said but chinese economists do not consider that the 
countrys inflation rate which they calculate differently than in 
the west 
in china the annual inflation rate is calculated by averaging 
price increases over 12 months rather than measuring the gap 
between prices from a given date to the same date 12 months later 
using this system zhang said consumer prices during the first 
six months of this year were an average of 13 percent higher than 
during the first six months of last year this is what the 
government considers the inflation rate 
china says inflation was 72 percent last year and 11 percent in 
the first quarter of 1988 
china has not previously released an inflation figure calculated 
by the western method as is the 19 percent figure so this could 
not be compared against last year 
zhang said food prices during the sixmonth period were an 
average of 169 percent higher than in the same period last year 
and clothing prices were up about 10 percent 
prices in chinas 32 major cities were an average of 144 
percent higher than in the first six months of 1987 but were 19 
percent higher in canton and 20 percent higher in hefei 
in major cities zhang said wages of onefifth of the 
population have failed to keep pace with inflation leading to a 
decline in living standards 
zhang did not link the high inflation to the nations 11 percent 
economic growth rate during the first half of the year and its 172 
percent industrial growth rate 
some chinese economists believe this pace of growth is fueling 
inflation by creating too high demand for raw materials 
transportation and energy 
inflation is one of chinas biggest economic problems under the 
reform program introduced in 1978 by senior leader deng xiaoping 
china is moving away from a system where the state sets prices and 
is allowing the market to determine prices 
a twotier price system has developed with key items such as 
grain and pork sold both in state stores at artificially low prices 
and on the free market at prices set by supply and demand prices 
of many other goods such as fruit are completely decontrolled 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

