<TEXT>
soviet inspectors today arrived 
at this air force base to perform the first check on us cruise 
missiles in britain under the superpower treaty that is to 
eliminate mediumrange nuclear weapons from europe 
twenty soviet inspectors landed at greenham common 50 miles 
west of london early this afternoon aboard an aeroflot jet the 
soviets were welcomed by a delegation of us and british officers 
the inspection visit is one of the terms of the 
intermediaterange nuclear forces treaty signed in moscow on dec 8 
by soviet leader mikhail gorbachev and president reagan 
the treaty provides for the elimination within three years of 
all nuclear missiles with ranges of 340 miles to 3000 miles and 
includes stringent inspection provisions to guard against cheating 
greenham common is one of two us cruise missile bases in 
britain the other is at molesworth 50 miles north of london both 
bases are run by us air force personnel but are technically 
british royal air force bases 
greenham common has 96 operational missiles and five backup 
missiles while there are another 16 operational missiles at 
molesworth according to the us military 
at greenham common a customs and immigration post was set up to 
receive the soviets and check the cameras geiger counters and 
other equipment they were allowed to bring for the inspection 
they are to stay overnight in converted servicemens 
accommodations at greenham common and are to eat meals at a 
cafeteria on the base 
under the treaty the inspectors may check the missiles and 
their mobile launchers which are to be taken back to the united 
states and destroyed but not the warheads 
at the bases the soviets may also place security men at all 
entry and exit roads to ensure no missiles are surreptitiously 
moved out the defense ministry said 
were entirely in the soviets hands said defense ministry 
spokesman martin helms they will say where they want to go 
the inspectors who will be flown to molesworth from greenham 
common will not be allowed to step outside the bases during their 
stay which is expected to last up to 4 days or until the 
inspection is completed 
us officers mostly from an onsite inspection agency based in 
west germany will accompany the soviets as they examine the 
missiles and launchers soviet inspectors first checked missiles in 
western europe on july 1 at two west german sites housing 
pershing2 rockets 
the current inspections are part of a 60day period of 
baseline inspections to determine the accuracy of data 
exchanged by the two sides the soviets are visiting 30 sites in 
the united states and western europe while us inspectors are 
visiting 133 soviet sites 
so far no violations have been discovered us officials say 
and the inspections are about 25 percent complete 
the soviets notified the british of their visit on monday 
officials said under the 16hour noticeofinspection rule 
in november 1983 greenham common was the first western european 
base to accept us cruise missiles under a december 1979 nato 
alliance accord 
</TEXT>
