the chief of soviet arms negotiations said today 
the kremlin will scrap a radar station the united states claims 
violates the antiballistic missile treaty if washington commits 
itself to the pact for at least 10 years 
however viktor p karpov chief of the foreign ministrys 
disarmament section repeated the kremlins contention that the 
krasnoyarsk radar station in siberia is aimed at monitoring space 
objects and is thus not covered by the 1972 treaty the pact 
restricts both superpowers defenses against nuclear missiles 
some advisers to president reagan are said to be recommending 
that he accuse the soviet union of committing a material breach 
of the treaty by operating the phrasedarray radar station they 
reportedly want him to abrogate the pact 
other reagan advisers have suggested reagan try to persuade the 
soviets to level the facility in the interest of preserving the abm 
treaty 
according to the pentagon a phrasedarray radar is able to 
track many object accurately meaning it could detect ballistic 
missiles and could potentially contribute to abm battle management 
karpov told a news briefing that construction work at the radar 
station has been stopped as a sign of good will 
this moratorium is still in force said the diplomat who 
once headed the kremlin negotiating team at the geneva arms talks 
superpower representatives are now negotiating a 50 percent cut in 
strategic nuclear weapons 
karpov said soviet envoys were seeking an agreement that would 
commit the superpowers to observing the abm treaty for at least 10 
years he called that commitment the necessary element for 
reaching an accord on halving superpower strategic arsenals 
in this framework we are prepared also for a radical solution 
to the krasnoyarsk radar issue raised by the americans karpov 
said 
if an understanding to abide by the abm treaty as signed in 
1972 is reached the soviet union will be ready to dismantle the 
krasnoyarsk radar in a verifiable way that would leave no doubts on 
the part of the united states he said 
the abm treaty limits how fast and far the united states can go 
in its search for a spacebased defense against ballistic missiles 
the socalled star wars program is being carried out under what 
the reagan administration describes as a strict interpretation 
of the treaty 
a broader interpretation would provide more leeway and 
scrapping the treaty would remove all legal restraints on the us 
program which the soviets oppose as a new and dangerous turn in 
the superpower arms race 
