<TEXT>
the soviet union offered tuesday to scrap a radar 
station the united states says is in violation of the 
antiballistic missile treaty if washington will honor the 1972 
pact for at least 10 more years 
viktor p karpov chief of the foreign ministry disarmament 
section also repeated the kremlin contention that the krasnoyarsk 
radar station in siberia is aimed at monitoring space objects 
and thus outside the abm treaty which restricts superpower 
defenses against nuclear missiles 
some advisers to president reagan are said to recommend that he 
accuse the soviets of making a material breach of the treaty 
with the phasedarray radar station and abrogate the agreement 
other advisers have suggested reagan try to persuade the soviets 
to raze the facility in the interest of preserving the abm accord 
according to the pentagon a phasedarray radar is able to track 
many objects accurately meaning it could detect ballistic missiles 
and contribute to abm battle management 
karpov who is in charge of soviet arms negotiations told a 
news briefing that construction work at the radar station has been 
stopped as a sign of good will 
this moratorium is still in force he said karpov once led 
the kremlin delegation to ussoviet nuclear arms talks in geneva 
where negotiators now are discussing a 50 percent cut in strategic 
nuclear weapons 
he said the soviet union wants an arrangement that would commit 
the superpowers to the abm treaty for at least 10 years describing 
that as the necessary element for such an agreement on 
longrange nuclear arms 
in this framework we are prepared also for a radical solution 
to the krasnoyarsk radar issue raised by the americans he said 
if an understanding to abide by the abm treaty as signed in 
1972 is reached the soviet union will be ready to dismantle the 
krasnoyarsk radar in a verifiable way that would leave no doubts on 
the part of the united states the abm treaty limits how fast and 
far the united states can go in its plan for a spacebased defense 
against ballistic missiles 
the strategic defense initiative commonly called star wars 
is being carried out under what the reagan administration calls a 
strict interpretation of the treaty 
broader interpretation would provide more leeway and scrapping 
the agreement would remove all legal restraints on the us 
program which the soviets say represents a new and dangerous stage 
of the arms race 
