<TEXT>
growers of hybrid corn for seed will have the 
option of planting their crop and not have it counted as a feed 
grain under 1988 acreage programs the agriculture department said 
tuesday 
acting undersecretary richard w goldberg said the hybrid seed 
corn may not be grown on acreage taken from production under 1988 
programs or on land enrolled in the longterm conservation reserve 
program 
further the additional acreage used to produce seed will not be 
counted when establishing base acreages for future feed grain 
crops he said farmers who decided to use this option will not be 
eligible for 1988 feed grain program benefits on the acres used for 
the seed crop 
goldberg said the action was taken to help offset the effects of 
drought on seed farms and to ensure that farmers will have enough 
seed for 1989 plantings 
the option is expected to be used primarily in southern areas 
where the growing season is longer interested producers can check 
with local offices of the agricultural stabilization and 
conservation service for further details he said 
