spokeswoman for us attorney henry hudson said the government had 
arranged a location which she would not identify where lawyers 
and those under subpoena could deliver records without being 
observed by reporters 
many of the subpoenas are to persons who are only potential 
witnesses in the investigation and not targets of it 
ms dibbley had no comment on the paisley motion to quash his 
subpoenas and said she knew of no objections filed to the other 
subpoenas 
the only recognizable figure to arrive for the morning session 
of the grand jury in the us courthouse was jack a sherman a 
civilian employee of the marine corps who supervised equipment 
purchases shermans office was searched by federal agents in a 
series of coordinated raids on june 14 which brought the nearly 
2yearold probe to public attention 
no one has been charged yet in the probe of the 
150billionayear pentagon purchasing system but government 
documents show that investigators are looking allegations that 
defense contractors and consultants many of them former military 
men bribed pentagon officials for contracting details that could 
be vital in winning contracts worth billions of dollars 
sherman who has been transferred to other duties pending the 
outcome of the investigation was a supervisory negotiator for the 
contracts division of installation and logistics office of the 
marine corps he has been a civilian employee of the marine corps 
since 1971 and was a civilian navy employee from 1957 to 1971 
according to pentagon records sherman is a gs14 making 
between 46600 and 60683 
neither he nor his attorney would comment on his appearance at 
the courthouse it could not be determined if he was actually 
brought before the grand jury 
other witnesses however were seen entering and leaving the 
grand jury room later in the day at a lunch break assistant us 
attorney joseph aronica who is in charge of the grand jury told 
reporters there wont be any luminaries during the first day 
the grand jury is expected to be back in session wednesday 
paisleys attorney e lawrence barcella said he filed a motion 
to quash the 11 subpoenas issued for paisley who served as 
assistant navy secretary for research engineering and systems from 
december 1981 to april 1987 when he became a consultant 
in addition barcella said we asked the government to affirm 
or deny whether they used illegal electronic surveillance even the 
fact that they may have gotten authorization does not mean their 
wiretap was applied for and carried out in a legal matter before 
we comply with a subpoena we want to insure that the government 
has carried out its responsibilities under the wiretap statute in 
an appropriate and accurate manner 
earlier the government released the search warrant for paisley 
which indicated that fbi agents were investigating whether he 
received payments from general dynamics mcdonnell douglas and 
pratt amp whitney while he worked for the pentagon the warrant also 
showed the government is investigating consulting work he has done 
since leaving the government for 10 different defense contractors 
at unisys blumenthal said in a letter to company employees that 
the giant computer company formed by the merger of sperry and 
burroughs had pledged full cooperation with hudsons investigation 
we expect and encourage each of our employees also to 
cooperate fully in responding to the governments inquiries 
blumenthal wrote 
the new management was installed at the former sperry 
surveillance and fire control division in great neck ny 
