<TEXT>
the veterans peace convoy of 31 american 
activists taking humanitarian aid to nicaragua was helped by the 
us governments attempt to keep it from crossing the border 
members said tuesday 
the publicity helped us greatly and poor people came to us 
throughout our trip to mexico city pushing coins into our hands 
and saying this is the least we can do said convoy 
coordinator raul valdez 40 of austin texas 
the support of mexicans has been great 
the caravan crossed the mexican border at nuevo laredo on july 
14 it now has 20 trucks with 20 tons of supplies 
the activists who oppose us policy aimed at overthrowing 
nicaraguas leftist sandinista government spoke with reporters 
after rain washed out a planned demonstration in front of the us 
embassy 
they originally planned to reach nicaragua in june to donate 
food medicine and other supplies but were delayed by us 
treasury department refusal to let them cross the border at laredo 
texas 
the us government said that leaving the trucks in nicaragua 
as they plan to do would violate a 3yearold trade embargo 
now the schedule calls for arriving in nicaragua on july 27 
after traveling through guatemala and honduras 
members of the group praised the hospitality they received in 
mexico 
its been fantastic said scott breindel of new york we 
stopped to ask this guy for directions to a hotel in mexico city 
and he just offered this compound where we could park our trucks 
and a place to stay for the night 
the american visitors noted that the foreign ministry and 
interior department arranged an official escort for their stay in 
mexico 
if they return to the united states without the trucks the 
activists face up to a 50000 fine and 10 years in jail each the 
us government said the vehicles could be used by nicaraguas 
sandinista government for military purposes and thus were subject 
to the trade embargo 
before the group entered mexico us customs agents asked us 
to sign a form that said we would promise to bring the trucks 
back said david silk 60 a world war ii merchant marine veteran 
from stonington conn 
it was another attempt to make it impossible for us to 
continue our journey said silk adding that no one signed the 
document 
silks truck is carrying more than 1000 pounds of paper donated 
by a local methodist church organization to print a bible in the 
language of nicaraguas sumo indians other activists are bringing 
food medicines and medical equipment 
the convoy also has sent 300000 tons of goods by ship to 
nicaragua whose government celebrated the ninth anniversary 
tuesday of its revolutionary victory over the rightist somoza 
dynasty that ruled nicaragua for four decades 
convoy leaders said they hope to obtain a ruling in federal 
court exempting their trucks from the nicaraguan embargo but they 
said that even if its not forthcoming they wont change their 
plans 
were going to donate this assistance to humanitarian 
organizations for the relief of human suffering said valdez a 
veteran of the vietnam war for that well risk any charges 
