<DOCNO> AP880719-0272 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
makers of domestic luxury sedans already plagued 
by a dwindling aging buyer base and a dull product image likely 
will lose market share in the next five years to foreign luxury 
marques slated to enter the domestic market according to industry 
consultant jd power 
in an interview monday power described a december survey of 
2100 luxurycar owners designed to identify the image of 22 luxury 
marques including four not yet sold in this country 
image itself is a vague concept of the general perception of a 
car including its advertising styling handling and performance 
and intangibles such as elegance 
power said the survey revealed a surprising lack of distinctive 
image among many luxury names those surveyed recognized only an 
average of 27 marques including the one they purchased within the 
18 to 24 months before the survey was taken 
some luxury cars do have a clear image mercedesbenz and jaguar 
particularly are considered elegant prestigious enjoyable to 
drive wellengineered contemporary but classically styled and 
distinctive power said 
but domestic makes overall are seen as conservative comfortable 
and unexciting he said that is despite individual successes such 
as ford motor cos lincoln division which has attracted more 
younger importoriented buyers while general motors corps 
cadillac buick and oldsmobile have not 
power said imagebuilding is a lengthy and costly process and 
may lag behind a marques actual sales as with lincoln 
but he said all domestic makers of luxury sedans likely will 
lose market share in the next five years to new entries such as 
nissans infiniti and toyotas lexus line both from japan and 
possibly to citroen and opel from europe 
the luxury car market in the united states peaked in 1986 with 
sales of 1176 million power predicted a downturn to 1 million in 
sales this year followed by a drop to 969000 in 1989 and a 
recovery to 1186 million sales by 1993 
the luxury markets recovery will be fueled partly by the entry 
of the new marques he said 
infiniti and lexus plan to offer six and eightcylinder engine 
coupes and sedans and hondas acura luxury line plans a sedan with 
an eightcylinder engine moving steadily in the arena dominated by 
the big three power said 
the new entries will find it easier to create solid distinctive 
images for their products because of their specialization and a 
lack of the poorquality and lookalike problems that marred 
domestic nameplates such as buick and oldsmobile power said 
also while 56 percent of luxury owners age 65 or older said 
they shop only for domestic models only 6 percent of buyers 
younger than 35 said they would not consider imports and 43 
percent of those younger buyers said they did not consider domestic 
cars at all 
as the younger buyers age and move further into the luxury car 
market the big three will be forced to design with them in mind 
and move their luxurymarque images in their direction if they hope 
to lure them away from japanese and european dealers power said 
in addition to lincolns success big three makers have begun 
improving and modernizing their images by offering sportier 
twoseat models such as the cadillac allante buick reatta and the 
muchdelayed chrysler turbo coupe by maserati 
european makers will not be similarly threatened as long as they 
continue moving their cars upward in price and exclusivity thus 
protecting their images he said 
</TEXT>
