<TEXT>
the swiss army knife is one of those 
products that keeps finding a new market from gis in the foxhole 
to yuppie campers on a weekend in the wild 
and thats good news for a small connecticut company that had 
the good sense to promote the handy pocket tool from forgotten 
sideline to bestseller 
the story of how the forschner group inc of shelton came to be 
the exclusive us marketer of swiss army knives is a classic tale 
of serendipity the companys founders picked up the knife in a 
search for good european cutlery for butchers years later new 
owners would move the little redhandled knives to the top of the 
line 
forschner sold more than 4 million of the knives in 1987 alone 
accounting for more than half the companys sales 
its a good business said james w kennedy forschners 
37yearold president and chief executive officer 
the knives manufactured by the victorinox cutlery co in 
switzerland are readily identified by their color and many 
gadgets the most popular model with about 500000 units sold in 
1987 is the classic a key chain model that has in addition to a 
knife blade a nail file scissors tweezers and a toothpick 
the latest addition to the more than 60 different models is the 
swisschamp which was introduced this year it has 29 features 
including a ballpoint pen pliers wood saw fish scaler corkscrew 
and magnifying glass 
the typical customer is a man between the ages of 21 to 35 
living in the northeast or northwest kennedy said the weakest 
sales for the knives are in the southeast 
the company whose stock is publicly traded had record sales of 
more than 364 million in 1987 up 24 percent from 1986 after 
expenses the company earned about 18 million the previous 
record was set in 1986 when forschner rang up 273 million in 
sales 
the swiss army knives which range in price from 8 to 18 for 
the classic to 90 for the swisschamp accounted for roughly 20 
million of last years sales 
the united states snapped up about 35 percent of victorinoxs 
output of swiss army knives in 1987 the sales have continued 
upward despite a more than doubling of the effective price of the 
knives in the past two years due to the declining value of the 
dollar kennedy said 
americans got their first exposure to the knives following world 
war ii when gis were stationed in europe kennedy said gis gave 
the name swiss army knife to the product because everyone in 
the swiss army carried it 
the rh forschner co started in 1855 as a manufacturer of 
butcher scales in new britain conn sometime during the 1880s it 
moved to new york city where it remained until relocating to 
shelton in 1976 it currently employs 80 people at its headquarters 
and a shelton warehouse where it does some assembly and repairs 
kennedy who started with the company in sales in 1975 was 
named president and chief operating officer in june 1987 he 
assumed the new title of chief executive officer this march 
the company after world war i started importing knives from 
germany because they were selling scales to the meatpacking 
industry so therefore they could assume the same people would 
buy knives kennedy said 
world war ii came along and their german source was naturally 
unavailable when the war ended the grandson of the founder 
went over to switzerland because germany was devastated and found 
this little company called victorinox that made very good butcher 
knives and he started importing them he continued 
the swiss army knife also made at the swiss factory was tossed 
in for good measure 
in 1957 the founding family sold rh forschner to a 
businessman who expanded the butcher knife segment and phased out 
the scale business in 1974 the business was sold again this time 
to marline resources co inc of new york city marline took the 
company public in 1983 
the business was purchased for the butcher knife business and 
lo and behold sitting there in the corner was the litte swiss army 
knife kennedy said 
we did a market research study of the whole company and the 
market research study indicated that we had a great opportunity 
with the swiss army knife 
the company turned up its marketing program for the knives in 
1976 when it introduced sealed display cases which are now used by 
10000 retailers to show off 10 to 20 knives 
it was a very successful program kennedy said it made it 
a silent salesman its always there in the store and frankly 
you dont get up in the morning and say im going to go out and 
buy a swiss army knife its something you know about and if you 
see it in a store it reminds you hey i will want one of those 
</TEXT>
