<TEXT>
batus inc received another setback tuesday in 
its attempted hostile takeover of farmers insurance group as 
idahos state insurance director rejected the proposed acquisition 
regulators in nine states where farmers has offices must approve 
the proposed 45 billion 63ashare offer and california and 
oregon already have rejected the buyout plan 
batus the us arm of british conglomerate bat industries plc 
filed an appeal in california and was expected to appeal in oregon 
anthony j fagiano director of idahos department of insurance 
stated that farmers in idaho hearings had cited a threat to the 
maintenance of its pocatello idaho regional office and the 
possible adverse effect on the southeast idaho economy if the 
office was closed 
farmers also cited its record of providing competitive medical 
malpractice liability insurance for idaho hospitals 
while batus officials did not assert they would close the 
pocatello office or discontinue medical malpractice liability 
insurance for hospitals in idaho their commitment contained 
significant reservations in the directors view fagianos 
statement read 
louisville kybased batus issued a statement that it was 
confident it could allay fagianos concerns and would immediately 
him to discuss with him the appropriate assurances on these 
points 
arizona has approved the takeover and hearings have begun or 
decisions are pending in illinois ohio and kansas a hearing in 
washington before that states insurance commissioner continued 
tuesday and another is planned in texas 
attorneys for farmers and its exchanges say batus could make any 
number of changes onces it takes over as sole owner including 
saddling farmers with a 16 billion acquisition debt 
during the many hearings farmers attorneys have cited 
recommendations made to batus by consultants it hired last year 
recommending that batus eliminate farmers life and medical 
malpractice insurance policies and its discounts for nonsmokers 
they also say batus could hike premium rates and shut down claims 
offices 
but batus has promised not to change farmers management and to 
let the company operate as it has 
batus which would borrow 32 billion of the 45 billion 
acquisition cost claims its parent company has such good credit 
that it does not need collateral and does not need a backup plan in 
the event later loan refinancing requests are denied 
batus has more than 40000 employees in its subsidiaries and 
ranked in the top 100 corporations in the united states last year 
with 58 billion in sales it owns saks fifth avenue and marshall 
fields and brown amp williamson tobacco corp a major cigarette 
maker 
</TEXT>
